segments.text: Was there any sort of exchange or let's say group criticism of papers in those early years at Woods Hole?
No, about the only criticism was that
There was the, we were free to publish without any supervision, but there was a thing called Woods Hole Contribution Number.
In order to get a Woods Hole Contribution Number, you had to hand it to the director and he would read it and say, okay, we have a Woods Hole Contribution Number.
So there was a great, there was that kind of indirect gimmick for getting the papers supervised a little bit.
But
No, right at the very beginning there was no, there was no really helpful review process.
The Woods Hole published a series called Papers in Physical Oceanology and Meteorology,
Those were largely reviewed for good English and so forth by the editor of that.
He was also the business manager and also an archaeologist who spent most of his time at Harvard.
He only had one business manager.
He was part town.
He had a secretary in later years who did all the purchasing and personnel and everything else.
I guess the
The first thing I ever wrote was not a scientific paper.
The first thing I ever wrote was a book, a popular book about oceanography.
It was before I came to the Oceanographic Institution.
It was probably a brilliant politic thing to do.
You know, you don't sort of write a book about medicine and then go to medical school.
But I went, I had, without some trouble, I wrote a book, a popular book on oceanography called Science of the Seven Seas.
It was published by Cornell Maritime Press in 1945, and I wrote a book about it.
I came to Woods Hole and was kind of embarrassed by it, why I didn't like it very much.
And so I thought maybe I ought to go to Scripps and get some kind of an education in oceanography.
I swear to have seen the book, unfortunately.
And so he wouldn't let me come in on account of the book, and basically he was kind of disgusting to me.
told that to say it wasn't all that bad at all.
But I don't have a copy anymore and I think there's a few, I know a few people have one.
Warren Wister has one, George Deacon has one.
It's a great challenge.
But I don't know.
I guess it only took me about three weekends to write
And, of course, spread it and worked very hard on his book, which came out the same time.
It sold quite well.
I think it made about $5,000 out of it.
At that time, my first salary was always $1,300.
So $5,000 was quite a lot of money to make.
I don't know any copies around it.
I'd systematically destroy them if I could find them.
What prompted the writing of that book?
Well, that's the interest of the field when I was doing that.
That got me interested.
That's the interest of the field.
I looked around the libraries and found various things.
Copycom stepped out and rewrote it.
And then began the scientific papers.
Yeah, that was the first thing I wrote.
That took me about two years to get started.
What about people outside of Woods Hole?
What kind of contact did you have with them?
That's interesting.
Very little.
I had, I know that, that Islin asked VanArts and me to teach his course in Harvard once or twice, which we did in 1948-49.
And I had a, and I taught for one or two years, by going once a week to Yale in a, in a
in a general science course that was held in front of the geological departments.
I think that might have been something like 1951, something of that sort, around that period.
But at those times we had almost no contacts outside.
And then we, about 1955,
The meteorological project that the Neumann had at Princeton broke up.
And Johnny and Phillips came from there to MIT.
And right away, we began to have a going relation with the people there at MIT.
And so every two weeks, we'd have a meeting.
and give some informal papers about what we were working on.
They were quite informal at that time.
And we'd have, it was Fridays, we'd have the meetings every two weeks, either at MIT or down here at Woods Hole, starting around 1955, I guess.
And that was very good.
It got people like C.C.
Lynn and Lou Howard and others interested in the, involved.
And the, that's become more institutionalized as time has gone on and somewhat more formal.
People are sort of scared to talk at night because there's so many high-powered people sitting around trying to shoot you down.
Don't you think people are a little bit scared?
Yeah, I think so.
But it didn't used to be that way.
So that was a very important thing to us intellectually, was that contact with the meteorology and mathematics department at MIT.
Well, that's a fair number at the mathematics department.

For example, one might not think so, but if you look at the publications that have come out of the math department, there's a very well-known book on rotating fluids that Harvey Greenspan wrote, for example.
Well, that would never have come if he hadn't had the contact with rotating fluid mechanical people that he had through these weekend seminars, these end-of-the-week seminars.
The one way that we managed to keep other people interested was that those things had never been restricted to oceanography.
been a little bit broader, so meteorologists or astrophysicists or something go dark out there as well, as long as there was some kind of large-scale fluid dynamics problem.
I thought you were going to say the way you kept them interesting is you served beer.
Well, yeah.
Well, actually, we didn't serve beer.
We served better things than that afterwards, but they had, but then we'd go to a restaurant or something.
Yeah, that was one of the problems.

We always managed to find some money at Woods Hole so we could have martinis or something, but at MIT they never seem to be able to have a slush fund, so it was a great source of embarrassment for people at MIT.
Harvard was rather good that way.
They could always come up with something.
But in the early days it wasn't Harvard, it was MIT and Woods Hole.
the first four or five years.
How often did these meet, once a month?
Twice a month.
Twice a month, okay.
Just about once a month.
Quite exciting.
Winter times, snow storms, it's quite exciting.
They weren't so very big, you know, perhaps two cars might drive up from here.
Four to eight people or something would go up each time and go down.
Sort of groups, I guess.
I think it was might have been 15 or 18 people.
As you leave Woods Hole and
moved first to Harvard, then MIT, did it seem to you as if the number of contacts that you were making narrowed, that you don't seem to have as much outside input as you thought you did?

Well, I think, I think I really probably, that's a little bit interesting, I think I've never made a very, at any time did I make a very serious effort to broaden my contacts at either Harvard or MIT.
I think I've had a tendency to
maintain contacts at Woods Hole as strongly as I could.

By the way, I've kind of been a little bit of an outsider at Woods Hole for 17 years now, but I guess I'm the only guy that's worked here for 17 years, the past 17 years without ever getting any salary from the place.
But
But by being here a good fraction of the time, it means that I don't have the, I can go into MIT faculty, but I would not know most people.
I wouldn't be sure if I went to some kind of a party event.
What was your reaction as a scientist in the 1960s involved in oceanography when you began to receive pressure from your students to eliminate your work with defense research?
Well, I was always sort of double-minded about defense research.
I accepted the necessity for doing a certain amount of it.
I didn't really want to work it.
defense research at all.
I registered as a conscientious objector, and so I had probably didn't do any secret research after I gave the infrared thing over to Bill Richeson in 1951.
I guess the reason why I came to Mattel to work on submarine, anti-submarine warfare was that somehow, somehow of all the things that, of all the circumstances under which you might really be
willing to kill people would be if you were under attack.
And the submarine seemed to me to be about as most clearly an attack weapon as many things could be.
Dropping a hash cannon on a submarine was somehow different from dropping a bomb on Hamburg, for instance.
And I felt that kind of, I felt that, you know, trying to find a way.
of some kind of compromise, and it seemed to me that that was my own personal compromise that I was willing to make.
So I really never kind of really
I was rather glad not to do any military research.
I mean, if you take someone like Walter Munk, for example, who all his life has been connected with chasing things, meetings, and post-sabotage missiles, and I don't know what things all his life.
I very early, I very early found it somewhat distasteful and decided to try to avoid it.

But I also didn't really want to make a big thing of it because I'm not so absolutely confident that my own personal view is a one that everybody in the country can afford to espouse and all these moral things are kind of valid.
And so I never could make a
a very good argument for pacifism, except it was something which was personally very strong in me.
And so, on the other hand, when we're all, when there were student
unrest and riots and so forth, I didn't really try to associate myself with those either.
We were people who wanted to become leaders of elements, pacifists or something like that, so I wasn't doing any...
I didn't feel vulnerable from students, but I didn't...
I was kind of curious, you know.
In a way, I didn't really...
I found some of their behavior kind of distasteful.
I went to Yale to get an honorary degree once and the ROTC students were there getting their commissions and the rest of the students there were just cheering and booing me.
And, you know, I didn't like that.
You know, I'd see these poor kids forgetting their commissions.
I couldn't, I'm not that kind of a pacifist.
I wanted to enjoy or encourage or anything like that.

I was sitting next to Art Buchwald, and he said, he was constantly against the board, and sort of went down on me, but these kids were made board, he says, and these two guys, and this is awful, he said, they're the, they're the, those ROTC students are the, are the, are the, are the greatest people here.
I guess one,
I guess, really, basically, no matter what everybody wants to do, I always want to do something different.
And if I happen to be in a, if I happen to be in a pacifist country, I'd probably be in a knowledgeable stance about that.
I have a feeling that's probably true.
It's a question of, you know, trying to, trying to
You're trying to suspend judgment.
You're trying not to be carried along with the crowd in some blind way.
And so you've got an overdose of antibodies, no matter what everybody else is doing.
You resist it.
So I mean, if I were in a conservative country, I'd be a liberal.
If I was in a liberal country, I'd be a conservative.
I just know rebellious.
In some way, I wouldn't want to.
I'd try to see the other side and maybe over-emphasize it.
But I wouldn't find it very strong.
It would just be my own personal feelings about it.
This is an obligatory question which you can choose not to answer.
Of all the work you've done, what do you consider your major accomplishment?
I don't know.
I guess I would want to make it the thing that I thought was the most fun, the biggest surprise.
I think...
I think the thing I like the best, you know, it's kind of crazy, I kind of like the salt fountain the rest of everything.
It's one of the least significant things I suppose there is.
I kind of like the salt fountain the best, although it seems to have almost no significance in the ocean at all.
I've tried rather hard to make it happen, but I kind of like it because it's just kind of so crazy.

I think as far as most significant things are concerned, I suppose the attempts to attempt to put together some kind of a wind-driven model of the ocean, an attempt to build some kind of theory of thermocline, thermal circulation of the ocean.
I guess from the objective point of view, those are the most
I think most things, more has grown out of those than other things.
Nothing much has grown out of the salt, not directly as far as the ocean is concerned.
Comments to prospective students.
What do you suppose will be, let's say for lack of a better word, the new hot field in oceanography?
For a while, nuclear physicists were sort of the in-group to be.
What do you think occurs next?
In oceanography?
In oceanography.
Oh, yeah.
Well, right now, a hot field right now is all the large-scale terminals and eddies.
That seems to be a hot field.
But I suppose that my feeling about a hot field is that
Maybe I'm wrong.
Well, there are certain obvious fields that people are going to go into, things which are very clearly going to happen, like an intensification study of equatorial phenomena, for example.
But those are, it's hard to, you're not really predicting very much when you say those things, because those things are already beginning to happen.
I suppose that there'll be a transformation of descriptive water mass chemical kind of oceanography into a quantitative science once the
proper language and computing technique and so forth is constructed in the middle hand.
If you look at this, there's a tremendous amount of oceanographic literature which is fairly descriptive on the basis of what muscles and capsules are.
And the ability to marshal all that information in some kind of a
of a systematic, balanced way so that it can, so that computations can be made easily and there's a range of validity.
There's a susceptibility to errors and so forth that can be laid out very clearly.
I suppose that that's going to be a
something's going to happen.
I can't believe that it's going to be in this chaotic qualitative state.
And somehow some very tidy-minded, clever people are going to be able to put the whole thing together in good ways.
But the standard
This really doesn't mean field work or anything.
This means just sort of a re-combination of certain descriptive elements that already exist.
I thought that for some time.
I don't seem to have the talents or the skills to carry it off.
I think Carol Walsh is coming close to it.
Not I don't know.
It's a very big fight tonight.
One feels that there are hundreds and hundreds of qualitative indications of what's going on in the ocean buried in the descriptive literature, never properly put together.
I mean, it's just as though, it's just as though you were, it's just as though you had some kind of a very very badly, if you had, suppose you had a few

of a crossword puzzle, of a jigsaw puzzle, but through some very bad diffusing eyeglasses, so you really couldn't see the fact that the pieces had interlocking sides, and all you could see was patterns of color and so forth.
And as you looked at it, you might try to take all the predominantly blue ones here, and all the red ones, and the green ones, and move them around, something like that.
See, what does this all mean?
But then, as soon as your eyes can see the fact that there are edges which can fit together, suddenly there's a new set of rules to the game.
And you put together this thing using hints from the covers.
but not using the color in some other kind of way.
And then all of a sudden, you can start to put the thing together.
And I think that we have all these hints, but we don't have the proper quantitative language or something to put the things together.
And at some stage, that may happen.
It could be exciting.
And all these qualitative things are very important.
For example, Worthington just came in yesterday or the day before.
I also put a print on my desk here, which is a paper that he just published, which is a big refutation of my business simulation model.
Now, you know, he's had it around for several years and didn't show it to me until he got it published on some desk.
Well, it's a very, it's a very interesting, it's a very interesting paper.
He says that the, that the Antarctic circuit, the Antarctic
bottom water isn't being formed anymore.
It hasn't been formed.
It's basically not being formed at all.

Now, most of us, myself and many other people, have always figured that the whole deep Pacific and Indian, Pacific and Indian oceans were filled up with a mixture predominantly of Antarctic bottom water.
It was going on.
So it was an overturn of something like once every thousand years.
It's a little bit of a disaster on the basis of some
some description of the cellocase, that there isn't any .
Well, one can conjure up arguments to try to demolish his thesis.
One can point out that he ignores features of numerical models that have already been made.
In fact, he's taken a very simple model of a steady-state geostrophic infection.
He's ignoring lateral mixing and all kinds of things like that.
Well, the way I feel about this is that probably he's, by looking around in the clever way he does at the information,
He's recognized some color to a few pieces of the puzzle that other people haven't seen.
But that he's overlooking certain things like the shapes of the jigsaw puzzle itself.
And so we haven't seen those, we haven't seen the colors of those things, which we do need as hints.
But at the same time, he's probably isolated some major constraint on the system, which is not quite as strong a constraint as he thinks it is.
And because we don't have ways of putting together in a systematic way other constraints like that over the whole ocean, we can't really
There's not so much to contend about, basically.
And someday, these important facts aren't going to be introduced one at a time, like dissociated from everything else that's ever been introduced.
All of these things, all of these ideas will come in in some balanced way to give an optimum picture of what the circulation is.
I don't know exactly how it's going to be done.
But I do know how to take his paper
and to relate it to some numerical models of the abyssal circulation, which make his case for zero energetic bottom-up formation very much weaker.
I don't want to abandon the important things that he discovers, but I think that the conceptual framework in which the argument is made is too narrow, too special,
and therefore those important facts don't quite mean what he thinks they mean.

And they ought to be related to a lot of other important facts all around the place, not just selective, like a lawyer makes a case for some particular thing, but use all the good evidence in some kind of way and see what it tells you.
And as long as we don't have some kind of way of manipulating it,

weighing, relating large amounts of different kinds of qualitative evidence, then the temptation to be a lawyer, just pick and choose those aspects of the thing which will defend a particular case, that temptation is always going to be there.
And so we don't want to be a bunch of lawyers arguing special cases.
We want some mechanism for a measured judgment.
which we can all agree what its elements are.
I think some numerical methods are going to be worked out.
I think that's going to be an exciting thing.
